1
00:00:06,916 --> 00:00:08,833
[man 1 over comm]
<i>Attention all flight personnel,</i>

2
00:00:08,916 --> 00:00:11,458
<i>please verify ready to resume count
and go for launch.</i>

3
00:00:11,541 --> 00:00:12,875
<i>- ITS?</i>
- [man 2] <i>We're a go.</i>

4
00:00:12,958 --> 00:00:14,333
- [man 1] <i>TTC?</i>
- [man 3]<i> Go.</i>

5
00:00:14,416 --> 00:00:16,333
- [man 1]<i> CBC?</i>
- [man 4]<i> Orbit group, go.</i>

6
00:00:16,416 --> 00:00:18,625
- [man 1] <i>BTC.</i>
- [static crackles over comm]

7
00:00:18,708 --> 00:00:20,458
[man 1] <i>BTC, your pole is go?</i>

8
00:00:20,541 --> 00:00:21,583
<i>Is that affirmative?</i>

9
00:00:21,666 --> 00:00:23,708
[man 5]<i> Yes, affirmative. BTC is a go.</i>

10
00:00:23,791 --> 00:00:26,125
- [man 1] <i>Copy that. OPS?</i>
- [woman 1]<i> We're a go.</i>

11
00:00:26,208 --> 00:00:27,500
- [man 1] <i>Electrical?</i>
- [man 6] <i>Go.</i>

12
00:00:27,583 --> 00:00:30,708
- [man 1] <i>SRO?</i>
- [man 7] <i>SRO is go. We're clear to launch.</i>

13
00:00:30,791 --> 00:00:32,291
- [man 1] <i>Guidance?</i>
- [man 8] <i>Go flight.</i>

14
00:00:32,375 --> 00:00:34,583
- [man 1] <i>Tito?</i>
- [woman 2] <i>Kingfisher is ready to launch.</i>

15
00:00:34,666 --> 00:00:37,291
- [man 1] <i>And CDR?</i>
- [woman 3] <i>CDR is go.</i>

16
00:00:37,375 --> 00:00:39,791
[man 1] <i>Okay. Commander Barnett,</i>
<i>on behalf of the Hyperion team</i>

17
00:00:39,875 --> 00:00:43,208
<i>and the millions of people watching
around the world, good luck, Godspeed,</i>

18
00:00:43,291 --> 00:00:45,625
<i>and we'll see you back here in two years.</i>

19
00:00:46,208 --> 00:00:49,041
[woman 3] <i>Thank you, Jim.</i>
<i>Our thanks to the launch team</i>

20
00:00:49,125 --> 00:00:50,833
and everyone at the MTS program.

21
00:00:50,916 --> 00:00:52,666
The crew is go for launch.

22
00:00:52,750 --> 00:00:55,041
[Jim] <i>Copy that.</i>
<i>We have a go for auto-sequence start.</i>

23
00:00:56,083 --> 00:00:59,166
<i>T-minus-15 seconds.
Stand by for terminal count.</i>

24
00:01:02,125 --> 00:01:06,708
<i>Ten, nine, eight, seven, six.</i>

25
00:01:06,791 --> 00:01:08,333
<i>We have main engine start.</i>

26
00:01:09,166 --> 00:01:12,291
<i>- Three, two, one, zero.</i>
- [exhales]

27
00:01:12,375 --> 00:01:14,375
[rumbling]

28
00:01:28,458 --> 00:01:32,125
<i>First-stage separation in three, two, one.</i>

29
00:01:34,541 --> 00:01:35,833
<i>Good break. Good break.</i>

30
00:01:46,083 --> 00:01:47,333
<i>Roger roll, </i>MTS.

31
00:02:02,208 --> 00:02:04,125
<i>We should have a good</i>
<i>forward link now, </i>MTS.

32
00:02:04,916 --> 00:02:07,041
Copy that. I'm seeing the same thing here.

33
00:02:10,541 --> 00:02:12,791
[Jim] <i>We're coming up</i>
<i>on second-stage separation.</i>

34
00:02:12,875 --> 00:02:14,583
Copy, second-stage separation.

35
00:02:22,958 --> 00:02:24,750
[Jim] <i>Altitude is 70 kilometers.</i>

36
00:02:24,833 --> 00:02:26,708
<i>One hundred and seventy kilometers
downrange.</i>

37
00:02:36,250 --> 00:02:38,625
Hyperion, the main engines
are underperforming slightly.

38
00:02:38,708 --> 00:02:41,416
- [Jim] <i>Copy, main engines underperforming.</i>
- Good read.

39
00:02:41,500 --> 00:02:43,541
[Jim] <i>Stand by. We're consulting flight.</i>

40
00:02:47,416 --> 00:02:48,541
Flip your visors down.

41
00:02:52,375 --> 00:02:54,375
[tense music playing]

42
00:02:57,000 --> 00:02:59,791
We're past return to landing. Abort
complete reaching the end of Oceanic.

43
00:02:59,875 --> 00:03:00,708
Abort?

44
00:03:10,333 --> 00:03:11,166
Hyperion?

45
00:03:13,416 --> 00:03:14,791
[Jim] <i>That's a negative abort, </i>MTS.

46
00:03:14,875 --> 00:03:16,875
<i>There's enough fuel
to handle the discrepancy.</i>

47
00:03:16,958 --> 00:03:18,125
<i>Negative abort.</i>

48
00:03:19,083 --> 00:03:20,875
Copy. Negative abort.

49
00:03:25,791 --> 00:03:28,291
[Jim] MTS, <i>you're leaving</i>
<i>for Mars Transfer Orbit.</i>

50
00:03:28,375 --> 00:03:29,875
<i>Final systems nominal check.</i>

51
00:03:32,791 --> 00:03:33,625
Are we a go?

52
00:03:34,208 --> 00:03:35,041
Go.

53
00:03:35,958 --> 00:03:36,791
Go.

54
00:03:39,250 --> 00:03:42,041
Roger, Hyperion. We're ready.
Go for MTO burn.

55
00:03:42,125 --> 00:03:44,333
[Jim] <i>Roger that.</i>
<i>Enjoy the ride, everyone.</i>

56
00:03:44,416 --> 00:03:47,666
<i>MTO in three, two, one.</i>

57
00:04:02,833 --> 00:04:04,375
<i>That's negative return, </i>MTS.

58
00:04:14,541 --> 00:04:16,083
<i>Past max Q.</i>

59
00:04:23,875 --> 00:04:27,750
<i>Main engine cutoff, three, two, one.</i>

60
00:04:28,833 --> 00:04:29,666
We go.

61
00:04:56,666 --> 00:04:58,416
[softly] Um... [clears throat]

62
00:05:07,666 --> 00:05:10,333
[tranquil music playing]

63
00:05:44,500 --> 00:05:45,708
[Barnett] There she is.

64
00:06:02,250 --> 00:06:04,750
[Jim] MTS, <i>we're approaching</i>
<i>Kingfisher separation.</i>

65
00:06:04,833 --> 00:06:06,625
Copy. Kingfisher separation.

66
00:06:08,458 --> 00:06:09,583
[thud]

67
00:06:14,833 --> 00:06:16,291
[Jim] <i>Separation is nominal.</i>

68
00:06:32,208 --> 00:06:34,791
[Barnett] <i>The Kingfisher</i>
<i>is auto-docked to the </i>MTS.

69
00:06:34,875 --> 00:06:37,000
<i>- Moving to taxi in now.</i>
- [Jim]<i> Copy that.</i>

70
00:06:53,708 --> 00:06:55,833
[Jim]
MTS, <i>what's the current closure rate?</i>

71
00:06:56,333 --> 00:06:59,000
[Barnett] Closure rate is nominal.
Five centimeters per second.

72
00:07:06,458 --> 00:07:07,791
<i>MTS </i>is in free drift.

73
00:07:09,833 --> 00:07:10,833
[exhales]

74
00:07:11,333 --> 00:07:12,416
Hang tight a bit.

75
00:07:14,958 --> 00:07:17,750
Tethered gravity spin is starting.
You're a go, Hyperion.

76
00:07:29,375 --> 00:07:31,375
Artificial gravity is climbing.

77
00:07:37,458 --> 00:07:39,500
Looks like we'll hit close to five G's.

78
00:07:45,916 --> 00:07:47,000
Tether's unspooling.

79
00:07:53,166 --> 00:07:55,166
[whirring]

80
00:08:09,750 --> 00:08:11,750
[David vomiting and coughing]

81
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:22,666
[Barnett] Solar array separation.

82
00:08:29,291 --> 00:08:30,208
[David sighs]

83
00:08:34,958 --> 00:08:37,125
[Barnett] TDS nominal and at full speed.

84
00:08:37,625 --> 00:08:38,625
[whirring stops]

85
00:08:40,625 --> 00:08:42,041
All right. Plugs out.

86
00:08:44,916 --> 00:08:47,666
Thank you for the launch, Jim.
See you again at the first check.

87
00:08:47,750 --> 00:08:49,958
Are you kidding me? That was incredible!

88
00:08:50,041 --> 00:08:52,583
- That was incredible! [laughs]
- Okay.

89
00:08:52,666 --> 00:08:53,541
Oh!

90
00:08:55,291 --> 00:08:57,750
- How are you feeling?
- I'm good. Good.

91
00:08:57,833 --> 00:08:59,833
[Zoe laughs]

92
00:09:22,208 --> 00:09:23,500
Oh...

93
00:09:25,666 --> 00:09:26,500
Let's go.

94
00:09:27,708 --> 00:09:29,708
[dramatic music playing]

95
00:09:42,250 --> 00:09:44,083
- [Zoe] I got it. Yeah.
- Oh. Thanks.

96
00:10:25,250 --> 00:10:26,291
Oh, God.

97
00:10:26,375 --> 00:10:28,916
Okay, Zoe, you take this one.
David, you start working in the back.

98
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:29,958
- This one?
- [David] Copy.

99
00:11:08,333 --> 00:11:10,541
- I'll be in the last wing.
- [Zoe] Copy that.

100
00:11:26,333 --> 00:11:28,083
- Hey. [knocks on wall]
- [David] Hey.

101
00:11:28,791 --> 00:11:31,250
- [Zoe] How you feeling?
- Uh...

102
00:11:32,125 --> 00:11:34,125
- You need anything?
- I'll be all right.

103
00:11:34,208 --> 00:11:35,041
A beer?

104
00:11:35,708 --> 00:11:36,625
So thoughtful.

105
00:11:38,791 --> 00:11:40,500
[exhales]

106
00:13:13,500 --> 00:13:14,333
[zipper opens]

107
00:13:14,416 --> 00:13:16,416
[mugs clinking]

108
00:13:19,791 --> 00:13:20,625
This will help.

109
00:13:21,541 --> 00:13:22,375
Thanks, Zo.

110
00:13:26,708 --> 00:13:27,625
[sighs]

111
00:13:43,666 --> 00:13:45,166
{\an8}- Come on, Zo.
- What?

112
00:13:45,666 --> 00:13:48,333
{\an8}- [David] Really?
- What are you...? I'm not...

113
00:13:48,416 --> 00:13:50,458
{\an8}Commander, how did she get Payloads
to allow this?

114
00:13:50,541 --> 00:13:53,500
{\an8}I don't even know anybody at Payloads,
so how would I...?

115
00:13:53,583 --> 00:13:56,791
You wasted, what, 800 grams

116
00:13:56,875 --> 00:13:59,458
of your allowable personal effects
on these?

117
00:13:59,541 --> 00:14:00,416
Mm-hm.

118
00:14:00,500 --> 00:14:03,916
- You don't even care about the rivalry.
- No. But you do, David.

119
00:14:04,625 --> 00:14:05,625
[Barnett chuckling]

120
00:14:05,708 --> 00:14:06,916
Oh, it's so easy.

121
00:14:08,500 --> 00:14:09,333
Okay.

122
00:14:10,833 --> 00:14:11,958
Five hours down...

123
00:14:13,875 --> 00:14:15,000
two years to go.

124
00:14:15,083 --> 00:14:16,000
[Barnett chuckles]

125
00:14:16,500 --> 00:14:18,416
As your doctor,
I'm telling you to drink that.

126
00:14:22,833 --> 00:14:24,833
[Zoe reading softly]

127
00:14:28,666 --> 00:14:31,250
- [David clears throat]
- "Applicable"? "Applicable"?

128
00:14:31,958 --> 00:14:33,583
- [David] "Applicable" is British.
- Is it?

129
00:14:34,333 --> 00:14:35,833
- How do I look?
- Stunning.

130
00:14:36,500 --> 00:14:38,333
No. I'm serious. This is a big deal.

131
00:14:38,416 --> 00:14:40,583
You look good. You look fine, seriously.
You look good.

132
00:14:40,666 --> 00:14:43,041
- [man speaking indistinctly over comm]
- [David clears throat]

133
00:14:43,125 --> 00:14:44,416
Oh. Good.

134
00:14:44,500 --> 00:14:47,041
Uh, yes, we do.
We read you loud and clear.

135
00:14:47,125 --> 00:14:49,041
Welcome to <i>MTS-42.</i>

136
00:14:49,125 --> 00:14:51,541
[man speaking indistinctly over earpieces]

137
00:14:54,000 --> 00:14:55,541
Oh, yeah. We did. Um...

138
00:14:55,625 --> 00:14:58,875
It's not uncommon to experience
a few hiccups during the launch,

139
00:14:58,958 --> 00:15:02,416
but due to the preparation
and expertise of our ground team,

140
00:15:02,500 --> 00:15:05,583
we had a smooth rendezvous
with the MTS Cycler.

141
00:15:07,500 --> 00:15:09,500
[man speaking indistinctly]

142
00:15:11,666 --> 00:15:13,000
That's true. Um...

143
00:15:13,500 --> 00:15:15,083
It's bittersweet.

144
00:15:15,166 --> 00:15:18,625
I've had the honor of participating
in two missions to date.

145
00:15:18,708 --> 00:15:21,500
<i>And I couldn't be working
with a more talented crew on this,</i>

146
00:15:21,583 --> 00:15:23,625
<i>my final and third mission.</i>

147
00:15:23,708 --> 00:15:25,708
[man speaking indistinctly]

148
00:15:26,416 --> 00:15:28,666
Um... well, it's only been a few hours,

149
00:15:28,750 --> 00:15:31,208
<i>but it's already
a life-changing experience.</i>

150
00:15:31,291 --> 00:15:32,833
<i>I'm thrilled to be here.</i>

151
00:15:35,458 --> 00:15:37,458
[man speaking indistinctly]

152
00:15:38,125 --> 00:15:40,500
[Zoe] <i>This isn't where</i>
<i>I thought I would end up.</i>

153
00:15:40,583 --> 00:15:43,708
<i>To me, my career was gonna be research</i>
<i>on Earth. </i>[chuckles]

154
00:15:43,791 --> 00:15:45,916
<i>You never know
where life's gonna take you.</i>

155
00:15:47,750 --> 00:15:50,208
Yes, I applied to the HARP program
because I thought

156
00:15:50,291 --> 00:15:53,125
it would be a funny story
to be rejected by Hyperion.

157
00:15:53,208 --> 00:15:54,250
[David & Barnett chuckle]

158
00:15:54,333 --> 00:15:57,666
[Zoe] <i>But now I realize</i>
<i>this is one of those rare opportunities</i>

159
00:15:57,750 --> 00:16:01,583
<i>that could truly give my life meaning
beyond anything I could imagine.</i>

160
00:16:02,083 --> 00:16:04,083
[man speaking indistinctly]

161
00:16:05,041 --> 00:16:08,166
Well, space exploration has always led
to amazing medical discoveries

162
00:16:08,250 --> 00:16:10,750
that are... applicable
to the people on Earth.

163
00:16:11,333 --> 00:16:14,375
- [David clears throat]
- [man speaking indistinctly]

164
00:16:14,458 --> 00:16:17,875
Well, uh, the launch was incredible.

165
00:16:19,166 --> 00:16:22,625
It does take a little while
to get adjusted to the artificial gravity.

166
00:16:25,291 --> 00:16:27,291
[man speaking indistinctly]

167
00:16:28,541 --> 00:16:31,291
[David] <i>Well, two years is a long time</i>
<i>to be away from my wife,</i>

168
00:16:31,375 --> 00:16:34,083
but this
is a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity.

169
00:16:34,166 --> 00:16:36,166
I am so grateful to have her support.

170
00:16:36,250 --> 00:16:38,291
[man speaking indistinctly]

171
00:16:38,375 --> 00:16:39,958
[David] <i>My research is integral</i>

172
00:16:40,041 --> 00:16:42,916
<i>to maintaining and sustaining life
on Mars long-term.</i>

173
00:16:43,625 --> 00:16:47,791
<i>We are taking the first steps
to being able to call Mars a second home.</i>

174
00:16:48,666 --> 00:16:50,666
[man speaking indistinctly]

175
00:16:50,750 --> 00:16:52,583
Uh, no. No, not at all.

176
00:16:52,666 --> 00:16:57,625
I mean, out of the thousands of proposals
submitted from university students

177
00:16:57,708 --> 00:17:01,791
<i>and professors all around the world,
these two definitely rose to the top.</i>

178
00:17:01,875 --> 00:17:05,000
<i>I'm more than confident in their ability
and their training.</i>

179
00:17:05,541 --> 00:17:08,166
I know they can handle anything
that comes their way.

180
00:17:24,750 --> 00:17:26,750
[machine powering up]

181
00:17:46,000 --> 00:17:48,000
[tense music playing]

182
00:17:59,791 --> 00:18:01,791
[whirring]

183
00:18:10,000 --> 00:18:12,041
[Barnett gasping]

184
00:18:12,125 --> 00:18:12,958
Oh, shit.

185
00:18:16,083 --> 00:18:17,625
[creaking]

186
00:18:18,375 --> 00:18:19,583
Oh, shit.

187
00:18:20,375 --> 00:18:21,666
[yells]

188
00:18:22,458 --> 00:18:24,791
[electricity crackling]

189
00:18:27,083 --> 00:18:28,375
[groans]

190
00:18:29,166 --> 00:18:30,041
[grunting]

191
00:18:31,833 --> 00:18:33,291
Commander! [gasps]

192
00:18:33,875 --> 00:18:35,166
Holy shit.

193
00:18:35,250 --> 00:18:37,250
- [David] Are you okay?
- Get him off! Get him off!

194
00:18:37,333 --> 00:18:38,208
What is going on?

195
00:18:38,291 --> 00:18:39,750
- [Barnett] Get him off!
- Are you okay?

196
00:18:39,833 --> 00:18:41,875
- [David] Is he alive?
- [Barnett] Just pull him up.

197
00:18:42,375 --> 00:18:43,375
Get him off.

198
00:18:44,250 --> 00:18:46,333
[Zoe]
Stop. Let's get him to the infirmary.

199
00:18:46,416 --> 00:18:47,250
I got him.

200
00:18:47,333 --> 00:18:50,416
- [David] Ready. [grunts]
- Ready? One, two, three. [grunts]

201
00:18:57,708 --> 00:18:59,083
- [David] Here?
- [Zoe] Yeah.

202
00:19:05,791 --> 00:19:06,750
[Zoe] That's good.

203
00:19:07,333 --> 00:19:09,583
- [David] Who the hell is this?
- Come on.

204
00:19:09,666 --> 00:19:10,791
[scissors snipping]

205
00:19:12,541 --> 00:19:14,541
[suspenseful music playing]

206
00:19:17,166 --> 00:19:19,166
[metal creaking]

207
00:19:19,250 --> 00:19:21,166
[air hissing]

208
00:19:21,250 --> 00:19:22,250
[gasps]

209
00:19:30,750 --> 00:19:33,291
- [Zoe] David, put some gloves on.
- [David] Copy.

210
00:19:46,375 --> 00:19:47,291
[Zoe] <i>Hold that closed.</i>

211
00:19:47,375 --> 00:19:49,666
- Just hold it as closed as you can.
- Wow.

212
00:19:50,791 --> 00:19:51,750
[Zoe] That's great.

213
00:19:53,250 --> 00:19:55,958
[Barnett] <i>The damage is contained</i>
<i>to the functional module.</i>

214
00:19:56,041 --> 00:19:59,791
<i>A significant amount of atmospheric O2
vented from the MTS.</i>

215
00:19:59,875 --> 00:20:02,208
There's a breach in the hull.
Getting all this?

216
00:20:02,291 --> 00:20:04,333
- [Jim speaking indistinctly over earpiece]
- Good.

217
00:20:04,916 --> 00:20:07,958
Hey, Jim. Who the fuck is on my ship?

218
00:20:09,000 --> 00:20:10,375
[Jim speaking indistinctly]

219
00:20:10,458 --> 00:20:14,000
Yeah. He's still unconscious,
but I mean... is he a threat?

220
00:20:14,083 --> 00:20:16,625
Do we need to, I don't know, find a way

221
00:20:16,708 --> 00:20:17,833
to restrain him or...?

222
00:20:19,250 --> 00:20:21,250
[whirring]

223
00:20:29,666 --> 00:20:31,000
Any idea if he'll wake up?

224
00:20:32,416 --> 00:20:34,500
Honestly, I'm surprised he's still alive.

225
00:20:43,541 --> 00:20:44,625
[David sighs]

226
00:20:45,208 --> 00:20:47,166
His name is Michael Adams.

227
00:20:47,250 --> 00:20:49,166
All they know for now
is that he's launch support.

228
00:20:50,791 --> 00:20:54,041
- [Zoe] How the hell was he missed?
- [Barnett] They're looking into it.

229
00:20:54,125 --> 00:20:56,000
We don't make mistakes like this.

230
00:20:56,083 --> 00:20:59,000
- Did he stow away on purpose?
- [Barnett] Hyperion doesn't know that yet.

231
00:21:04,000 --> 00:21:05,916
[Zoe] How are you not screaming in pain
right now?

232
00:21:07,083 --> 00:21:09,750
It... hurts.

233
00:21:10,916 --> 00:21:12,083
This is pretty serious.

234
00:21:13,666 --> 00:21:17,333
- [Barnett] How long?
